	<h2>
			<a href="/index.php/79-python-resources/109-while-true">
		While True</a>
		</h2>








<p><strong>By Danial Acevedo (edits by Lucy Chen and Eric Carb)</strong></p>
<p>## UNDERSTANDING WHILE TRUE ##</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">‚Äúwhile True‚Äù is a loop briefly mentioned in ICS 32. However, it's easy to misuse this loop, which can lead your program to crash or yield unexpected results.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Let‚Äôs start with a simple code example.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">while True:<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; print(‚ÄúUCI‚Äù)</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The code within while loops repeatedly execute as long the statement after "while" is true. Since "True" is always true, this code will print ‚ÄúUCI‚Äù (without quotes) infinitely.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">while True will keep looping until something within the loop interrupts it.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Many different ways to stop a while True loop exist, but we‚Äôll focus on two of Python‚Äôs built-in methods: break and return.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The break method simply means that, for whichever loop you‚Äôre currently running, break out of it once you hit the break statement. An example is below.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">while True:<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; print(‚ÄúUCI‚Äù)<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; break</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">‚ÄúUCI‚Äù will print once. Then break will terminate the loop, so nothing else prints.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">However, let‚Äôs say we have a situation where we needed to print something out a finite number of times:</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">i = 0<br />while True:<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; print(‚ÄúUCI‚Äù)<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; i += 1<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; if i == 5:<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; break #stops the loop</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The variable i starts at 0. Each iteration of the loop prints "UCI" on a line and adds one to i. After the fifth "UCI" prints, adding one to i makes 5. This satisfies the if, and break ends the innermost loop, which is the while True since there is only one loop. The end result is ‚ÄúUCI‚Äù printed on five lines. (Create a similar "while True" loop on pythontutor.com. The site will walk you through the code step-by-step. It may help you visualize what is going on.)</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Before we move on to return, remember: break only breaks the loop that you are in. So, if you had a while loop inside another one (shown below), you would need two breaks to exit both while loops.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">while True: <br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; print(‚ÄúUCI‚Äù)<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; while True:<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; print(‚ÄúZOT‚Äù)<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; break</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">This will make your program break the second while True loop, but the outer loop will continue to run.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">while True:<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; print(‚ÄúUCI‚Äù)<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; while True:<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; print(‚ÄúZOT‚Äù)<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; break<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; break</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">This will break both while loops.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Please note that you will very rarely, if ever, need to use nested while True loops.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The other way to break out of the while True loop is using a return statement. Return differs from break in two significant ways:</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">1. It must be used within a function.<br />2. Since return statements will end a function, using it will break out of all loops at once. the function's returning something, it ends once you hit the return statement. So, no matter how many loops inside of loops you have, a return will end the function.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Using while True can become useful for prompting the user for input in cases where the program has to check its validity before returning a value. This will come in handy when designing games, such as ConnectFour and Othello, as you see in ICS 32.</p> 
	
